# CRM RBAC and Multi-Tenant Standards

## RBAC Is Foundational
- Treat RBAC as mandatory in every module from day one.
- Authorization must be enforced in both backend and frontend paths.
- Never ship a route/page/action without permission checks.

## Centralized Authorization
- Use a centralized RBAC service in `packages/rbac`.
- Backend must check permissions for API access and mutations.
- Frontend must also apply permission-aware UI behavior:
  - Hide inaccessible features when appropriate.
  - Disable restricted actions with clear UX states.

## Tenant and Role Model
- CRM side supports internal staff with global roles.
- Partner Portal supports organization-scoped roles.
- Partner organizations must be able to define custom roles.
- Permissions must support granular module scopes such as:
  - `view`
  - `write`
  - `admin`

## Resource-Aware Enforcement
- Every permission check must support role-based and resource-based constraints.
- Avoid broad role-only checks when resource ownership/scope matters.
- Prefer reusable guards/helpers over inline ad-hoc logic.

## Auth Integration
- Use `NextAuth.js` or `Clerk` only if integration preserves full RBAC capabilities.
- Auth session/user context must carry role and org scope required for checks.

## First-Phase RBAC Priorities
- Global + organization-scoped role/permission support.
- RBAC coverage for dashboards, organization management, and inventory workflows.
- Block merges when module features bypass RBAC checks.
